'''Northwest Woodworkers Gallery''' (formerly Northwest Gallery of Fine Woodworking)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jennifer|first=Hicks|title=Seattle gallery shows off best work|journal=Woodshop News|date=July 2012|url=http://www.woodshopnews.com/at-the-galleries/502149-seattle-gallery-shows-off-its-best-work}}</ref>  in downtown [[Seattle]], is the oldest and largest woodworking [[cooperative]] in the United States. Started in 1980 in the [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] neighborhood by a small group of [[studio furniture]] craftsmen, the gallery has grown and fostered the resurgence of the Northwest Crafts movement.  The co-op includes notable master woodworkers such as [[Evert Sodergren]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Living Treasures: Evert Sodergren, Master Woodworker|url=http://www.seattlechannel.org/videos/video.asp?ID=2251|publisher=Seattle Channel|accessdate=2004-06-28}}</ref>  and [[Stewart Wurtz]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Rebecca|first=Teagarden|title=Studio furniture-makers transcend nature, one unique piece at a time|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/pacificnw/2008465016_pacificpnwl07.html|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=12/7/2008}}</ref> Northwest Woodworkers gallery moved to the 2111 1st Ave in the [[Belltown, Seattle|Belltown]] neighborhood in 2012. The gallery currently represents more than 200 woodworkers, including 27 members.

